item.text: Help the client facilitate mourning and manage their current and future life

Tip #1
Conceptualize grief work as being on a journey with the client. Grief strategies are the stops you make along the way.

Tip #2
In grief work, Session 2 should primarily be focused on having the client discuss their relationship with the deceased, the circumstances surrounding the death, and who is there to support the client. Session 3 should primarily be focused on helping the client explore new relationships and re-establish old relationships and interests. Please follow this session roadmap while maintaining flexibility (e.g., if the client wants to explore new relationships in Session 2, do not shut them down) and note that sometimes you may begin Session 3's work early.

Tip #3
Frequently used IPC techniques for grief:
  •  Decision Analysis
  •  Skills Building
  •  Role Play

• Talk about the importance of the relationship, both positive and negative experiences
• Mourn and accept the death. Talk about the death and how it impacted the client
• Be mindful of cultural norms during discussion, especially when asking about negative aspects of the relationship
• Explore new relationships and re-establish old relationships and interests

Tip #1
Navigate between this and the IPC Techniques Screen to use IPC strategies and techniques to address the identified problem area. On both screens, scroll to a strategy or technique you would like to discuss and click on its dropdown menu to see example guiding prompts.

Tip #2
Use the prompts below as a guide. The session should flow like a conversation, so do not ask every single question listed and engage the client as you see fit. You can also come up with your own questions.

valueCoding.display: Tell me about your relationship with the deceased
What does this person mean to you?
How did you spend time together?
What do you miss?
Were there ups and downs in the relationship? Lets talk a little bit about that
Was there ever a time in which the relationship was not how you wanted it to be? Were you able to resolve that?

item.text:
Tip #1
Go into the circumstances of the death. If already discussed in Session 1, there is no need to ask again.

Tip #2
In many cultures, it is not appropriate to talk about the person's death. Be sensitive to that. Consider your clients cultural beliefs about speaking about the deceased. If you notice any reluctance from the client, do not ask these questions.

valueCoding.display: Tell me about how this person died
Were you there?
Was it a long illness? If it was, were you part of caregiving? Were there any conflicts that emerged with family members during caregiving?
Were you able to follow the customs that would have given you comfort after this person died? Did anyone help you?
Do you have regrets?

How are you managing your grief in your current life?

How do you spend your time?

Are there activities you want to try that you have not done before? Are there places you might want to visit?
How do you see your future since this person's death?

item.text: Use IPC techniques to address the identified problem area

Navigate between this and the previous screen to use IPC strategies and techniques to address the identified problem area. On both screens, scroll to a strategy or technique you would like to discuss and click on its dropdown menu to see example guiding prompts.

Definition
We often refer to Decision Analysis as "brainstorming". Here, the client comes up with multiple options or ideas to solve a problem. At first, no option should be eliminated and the brainstorming process should allow for a wide range of possibilities, even the silly and likely impossible ones. Next, consider the pros and cons of each option. Finally, come up with a plan of action.

Tip #1
Encourage the client to generate and actively choose their own options. Do not provide them with pre-determined options. If the client gets stuck on generating options, you can offer them an option. However, make sure that this option is not the best suggestion. This will encourage the client to generate better ideas.

Tip #2
If there are multiple steps involved in the clients decision-making process, prioritize what to do next by asking: "Of these steps you need to take, what is the most important to do first?"
Example guiding prompts (not all questions need to be asked)

valueCoding.display: What are your options?
Let's make a list of options we come up with
Lets look at the pros and cons of each option
Which option or combination of options would you like to try?

item.text: This technique is used to help the client improve communication by improving their interpersonal skills.

valueCoding.display: Find a good time to have the conversation ("strike while the iron is cold")
Use "I" statements (culturally specific!) and communicate your needs
Focus on the specific situation
Convey what you want (directly or indirectly)
Attempt to understand, not necessarily accept, the other person's point of view
Have a few options in mind
Avoid words like "always" and "never"
Don't focus on the past. Stay with the current problem
Is there room for compromise (give to get)?
If powerless, identify advocates/supporters
BE SAFE (De-escalation of arguments)
Show the person your appreciation if they give you what you need

item.text:
Definition
This technique is used to help the client practice how to change their interactions with someone. This practice is done in the office before the client tries it at home.

Tip #1
When introducing Role Play to the client, you can compare this activity to practicing before a sporting event or a musical performance.

Tip #2
You can also do a modified Role Play, in which the client plays both themselves and the other person. The advantage of a modified Role Play is that the client may have a better understanding of how the other person would respond in an interaction, making the rehearsal before the real event more realistic.
Example guiding prompts (not all questions need to be asked)

valueCoding.display: Lets practice what you could say. Then, let's think about what the other person may say back. I could play the other person.
Lets try out what you are going to say before you say it at home. Rehearsal before the real event helps you work out the bugs.

item.text:
Definition
This technique allows the client to use the skills they worked on during the session at home.

Tip
To address at home the problems associated with their distress, the client will leave the session with a plan, often based on what has occurred during Role Play practice. Before the client goes home, prepare them for three possible outcomes and let them know that you would like them to come back to discuss the results regardless of what happens:
  •  The client may decide not to try the Work at Home
  •  The client may try the Work at Home, but it does not go well
  •  The client tries the Work at Home and it goes well
Example guiding prompts (not all questions need to be asked)

valueCoding.display: How do you feel about trying what we have practiced?
Would you want to try this at home

item.text:
Definition
In this technique, the provider asks the client to describe in detail a recent conversation or argument that they have had with another person. During the Analysis, ask for direct dialogues and discuss how the client felt during the conversation, what they wanted to accomplish, and what they did not say but wish they had communicated.

Tip #1
You can conduct a Communication Analysis on either an argument that went badly or an argument that ended well. You can also choose to do an Analysis on an important conversation. It does not have to be an argument.

Tip #2
You can conduct a Communication Analysis on the clients text message exchanges with the other person.
Example guiding prompts (not all questions need to be asked)

valueCoding.display: How did the conversation start?
Where were you and who spoke first?
What did you say? What was your tone? Show me.
What did the other person say? What was the other persons tone?
How did you feel before the conversation started, how did you feel during the conversation, and how did you feel after the conversation?
How did you feel when you said X? How did you feel when the other person said Y?
Did you say everything you wanted to?
How did the words make you both feel?
How did the conversation end?
What do you wish you had said differently?
What was the other persons point of view? Could you hear it?

item.text: Help the client resolve the disagreement by improving their interpersonal skills, accepting that things may not change, or ending the relationship

Tip #1
Please see descriptions of the 3 possible disagreement stages and your goals for each stage:
    1) Renegotiation (still actively working on the dispute) is when parties are arguing to find a solution but need help. The goal is to help the client build skills, explore differences in expectations, and find alternative solutions.
    2) Impasse (stuck) is when parties stop communicating and are stuck on resolving the problem. The goal is to help the client make the active choice of staying or leaving. If the client decides to stay, help them accept and work on not allowing the situation to stimulate distress.
    3) Dissolution (end the relationship) is when one or more parties want to end the relationship.The goal is to help the client leave the relationship in the least harmful way possible.

Tip #2
Note that disagreement could be with an organization as well.

Tip #3
Frequently used IPC techniques for disagreements:
  •  Communication Analysis
  •  Decision Analysis
  •  Role Play
  •  Work at Home
  •  Skills Building

• Identify the disagreement and its stage: Renegotiation (still actively working on the disagreement); Impasse (stuck); or Dissolution (wish to end the relationship)
• Assess for violence
• Look at differences in expectations between the client and the person in disagreement
• Ask the client to put themselves in the other persons shoes

Tip #1
Navigate between this and the IPC Techniques Screen to use IPC strategies and techniques to address the identified problem area. On both screens, scroll to a strategy or technique you would like to discuss and click on its dropdown menu to see example guiding prompts.

Tip #2
Use the prompts below as a guide. The session should flow like a conversation, so do not ask every single question listed and engage the client as you see fit. You can also come up with your own questions or prompts.

Tip #1
Identify the client's expectations and the other persons expectations. Explore whether these expectations are shared or not and whether they are reasonable and realistic.

Tip #2
Explore how the client and the other person communicates during disagreements.

valueCoding.display: Can you describe a recent disagreement?
What do you see as the problem between the two of you?
What are you arguing about?
What does the other person want?

item.text: The goal of life changes work
Assist the client in managing their feelings around the loss of the old role and help them adjust to the new role

Tip #1
In life changes work, Session 2 should primarily be focused on helping the client discuss and mourn the old role. Session 3 should primarily be focused on helping the client manage the new rolefeelings about the new role and skills and opportunities that can be brought from the old to the new role. Please follow this session roadmap while maintaining flexibility (e.g., if the client brings up the new role in Session 2, do not shut them down).

Tip #2
Frequently used IPC techniques for life changes:
  •  Decision Analysis
  •  Role Play
  •  Work at Home
  •  Skills Building

• Explore feelings about the loss of the old role: What was lost and what does the client miss?
• Explore feelings and challenges of the new role: Are there any skills and opportunities that can be carried over from the old role to the new life situation?
• Develop new skills and relationships to support the new role
• Discuss opportunities/options and adjustment to the new role

Tip #1
Navigate between this and the IPC Techniques Screen to use IPC strategies and techniques to address the identified problem area. On both screens, scroll to a strategy or technique you would like to discuss and click on its dropdown menu to see example guiding prompts.

Tip #2
Use the prompts below as a guide. The session should flow like a conversation, so do not ask every single question listed and engage the client as you see fit. You can also come up with your own questions or prompts.

valueCoding.display: We've been talking about the life changes you are experiencing that are related to your current symptoms
How do you feel about these changes?
How are you managing them?

item.text: Look for opportunities to talk about what has not been so great about the old role.

valueCoding.display: What do you miss from your old life?
Are there parts that you don't miss?
Are there parts that are still the same?
Are there parts that may be better?
Tell me about the good and the not so good

item.text:
Tip #1
Discuss the challenges and possible opportunities of the new role. Work with the client to find options to manage the role better and encourage them to identify skills and people in their life that will make the new situation easier.

Tip #2
If the client shares that they have no one to help them in the new role, help them brainstorm who can offer support.

Tip #3
Keep in mind that it may not be a person but an organization that can offer help.

valueCoding.display: Let's talk about your new situation (new role)
What are the challenges?
Do you have any regrets?
What are the things that are difficult and that you dont like about the new situation?
Are there new opportunities?
Have you asked for help?
Who is there to help you in this new role?

item.text: Everybody feels lonely sometimes, particularly when they go through big life changes. However, some people have long standing struggles connecting with others and may hesitate to initiate social connections. The goal is to help the client connect with others by increasing initiation and interaction with others.

Frequently used IPC techniques for loneliness or isolation:
  •  Decision Analysis
  •  Role Play
  •  Skills Building
  •  Work at Home

• Reduce loneliness or isolation by understanding its history: Explore how longstanding the loneliness is, how it started, and what the clients current exchanges with other people are

• Encourage and assist the client in developing new relationship skills and opportunities to meet people

Tip #1
Navigate between this and the IPC Techniques Screen to use IPC strategies and techniques to address the identified problem area. On both screens, scroll to a strategy or technique you would like to discuss and click on its dropdown menu to see example guiding prompts.

Tip #2
Use the prompts below as a guide. The session should flow like a conversation, so do not ask every single question listed and engage the client as you see fit. You can also come up with your own questions or prompts.
Use the information you have gathered from the Interpersonal Inventory in Session 1 to guide this discussion.

item.text: Use IPC techniques to address the identified problem area

Navigate between this and the previous screen to use IPC strategies and techniques to address the identified problem area. On both screens, scroll to a strategy or technique you would like to discuss and click on its dropdown menu to see example guiding prompts.

Definition
We often refer to Decision Analysis as "brainstorming". Here, the client comes up with multiple options or ideas to solve a problem. At first, no option should be eliminated and the brainstorming process should allow for a wide range of possibilities, even the silly and likely impossible ones. Next, consider the pros and cons of each option. Finally, come up with a plan of action.

Tip #1
Encourage the client to generate and actively choose their own options. Do not provide them with pre-determined options. If the client gets stuck on generating options, you can offer them an option. However, make sure that this option is not the best suggestion. This will encourage the client to generate better ideas.

Tip #2
If there are multiple steps involved in the clients decision-making process, prioritize what to do next by asking: "Of these steps you need to take, what is the most important to do first?"
Example guiding prompts (not all questions need to be asked)

valueCoding.display: What are your options?
Let's make a list of options we come up with
Lets look at the pros and cons of each option
Which option or combination of options would you like to try?

item.text: This technique is used to help the client improve communication by improving their interpersonal skills.

valueCoding.display: Find a good time to have the conversation ("strike while the iron is cold")

Have a few options in mind

Don't focus on the past. Stay with the current problem
Is there room for compromise (give to get)?
If powerless, identify advocates/supporters
BE SAFE (De-escalation of arguments)
Show the person your appreciation if they give you what you need

item.text:
Definition
This technique is used to help the client practice how to change their interactions with someone. This practice is done in the office before the client tries it at home.

Tip #1
When introducing Role Play to the client, you can compare this activity to practicing before a sporting event or a musical performance.

Tip #2
You can also do a modified Role Play, in which the client plays both themselves and the other person. The advantage of a modified Role Play is that the client may have a better understanding of how the other person would respond in an interaction, making the rehearsal before the real event more realistic.
Example guiding prompts (not all questions need to be asked)

valueCoding.display: Lets practice what you could say. Then, let's think about what the other person may say back. I could play the other person.
Lets try out what you are going to say before you say it at home. Rehearsal before the real event helps you work out the bugs.

item.text:
Definition
This technique allows the client to use the skills they worked on during the session at home.

Tip
To address at home the problems associated with their distress, the client will leave the session with a plan, often based on what has occurred during Role Play practice. Before the client goes home, prepare them for three possible outcomes and let them know that you would like them to come back to discuss the results regardless of what happens:
  •  The client may decide not to try the Work at Home
  •  The client may try the Work at Home, but it does not go well
  •  The client tries the Work at Home and it goes well
Example guiding prompts (not all questions need to be asked)

valueCoding.display: How do you feel about trying what we have practiced?
Would you want to try this at home

item.text:
Definition
In this technique, the provider asks the client to describe in detail a recent conversation or argument that they have had with another person. During the Analysis, ask for direct dialogues and discuss how the client felt during the conversation, what they wanted to accomplish, and what they did not say but wish they had communicated.

Tip #1
You can conduct a Communication Analysis on either an argument that went badly or an argument that ended well. You can also choose to do an Analysis on an important conversation. It does not have to be an argument.

Tip #2
You can conduct a Communication Analysis on the clients text message exchanges with the other person.
Example guiding prompts (not all questions need to be asked)
